comics.topTitle: The life-giving power of bird poo:
The Kookaburra and the Miner Bird:

Owen-Wright-Mural.description: I was commissioned by Northern Beaches council to work on the Open Art Cube project (run by my good mate Pat) during the World Surf League Narrabeen Cup event alongside some good mates and talented artists.

The brief was handed to us by the council and that was to paint an Aussie surf legend, so I chose Olympian Owen Wright, added a Kookaburra on his shoulder and one of my surfing Koalas in the background.
I'm not used to doing portraits so this was a refreshing challenge and Owen and his family loved it!

manly-carpark-booth-2020.description: Northern Beaches Council asked me to create an artwork that would wrap around an old toll booth at the entrance of a council car park located in Manly. I saw this as an opportunity to bring a hit of colour to an otherwise bleak, grey and aesthetically oppressive public environment. My idea to incorporate large scale Kangaroo characters with my signature pastel colour palette and boomerang shapes brought the space to life and provides warmth for commuters entering and exiting the car park.

manly-vale-b-line-cabinet-2019.description: I was commissioned by Transport for New South Wales to create an artwork for the Manly Vale B-Line bus stop, one of the many bus stops along the B-Line bus corridor. The goal was to enrich the B-Line bus route with artworks and photographic works from local artists, illustrators and photographers.

My work for this project is called ‘Creatures of Manly Dam’ and it’s a celebration of the biodiversity in the area and all the amazing native animals that call Manly Dam home. The hero of the work is the Eastern Pygmy Possum that’s been in some trouble in recent times due to land clearing. They’re beautiful little animals, and I wanted to use this opportunity to shine a light on them and their predicament.

manly-laneway-mural-2019.description: As part of their safer laneways project, the Northern Beaches council needed to make a dark, intimidating passageway safer for the community so instead of installing security cameras they opted for public art. This was a huge project that took 3 months to complete and spanned a 50 metre enclosed laneway that led from a council carpark to Manly Corso.

I saw this as an amazing and unique space that could be transformed to give something back to the community and to be used as an educational piece. My vision was to fill the entire space with Australian native wildlife endemic to the local area of the Northern Beaches and to highlight how damn cool they all are.
Here’s what the laneway looked like before we started painting.

It took many weeks to cover the entire laneway in the first base coat of paint. We worked from 8pm to 3am on week nights to avoid foot traffic and to observe a safe working environment. We were also restricted to using rollers and brushes and no aerosol as the ventilation in the space was poor. Big thanks to Cam from the council who organised a small army of youth to come and help during this stage.
The space really started to come to life once we applied our first base coats.
Once the base coats were down it was time to start on the animals. We spent many weeks filling the space with local native wildlife characters, here are some process shots of the team at work

bondi-beach-mural-2019.description: In the winter of 2019, Waverley Council gave us the opportunity to paint our first mural and what a place to paint a first bloody mural! Nervous and excited, Tash and I headed down to Bondi beach and got crackin' on the wall. Being our first mural, we definitely made some mistakes (wrong brushes, undercoat prep time etc.), but overall we were so stoked with the finished work. It took us three days in total and what a beautiful experience it was painting in the sunshine, glancing at the surf and chit chatting with the locals and visitors. Tash even paddled out for a quick surf and caught the best wave of her life!

Bondi is naturally a place of fun, sun and surf and for this mural I wanted to capture that same playful spirit and make it appeal to visitors and locals of all ages. I filled my work with quirky Aussie wildlife characters (of course) with a backdrop of abstract trees and boomerang shapes. The surfing Koala is the hero of the piece and this little guy is a recurring motif in my work which serves as a subtle nod to the plight of our beautiful Koalas.

The piece was installed over 3 days with paint, rollers and brushes. It's still on the wall as of writing so if you're ever in Bondi go down and check it out along with work from other local and international street artists and graffiti writers.
Here’s a few more photos of the process. What an experience we had painting this mural and fingers crossed we get to head back down to Bondi again to paint another one.

Coopers-Brewery.description: Coopers wanted to collaborate with an Australian artist for their 'Forever Original' campaign and I was lucky enough to fit the bill. I created artwork to go up as murals in venues, airports and festivals all over Australia. On top of the murals we also worked on a huge variety of Coopers x Brentos branded merch to compliment the campaign.

Nets-Out-Now-Campaign.description: I worked with the team at Envoy Film on some campaign imagery for the Nets Out Now campaign. We agreed the imagery should convey a positive message rather than one of graphic images. Shark nets aren’t the best for marine life with many non targeted and targeted species being tangled up and ultimately succumbing to the dirty tech that aims to give a false sense of security for ocean goers. Find out more at www.netsoutnow.com.au.

Tawny-Grogmouth-2.description: In 2021 I collaborated with Buckettys Brewery and Tawny Frogmouth magazine on a fundraising beer launch. We raised $10,000 for WIRES and the can design scored #9 in GABS beer can design awards in Australia and #1 can design in NSW. We loved this collaboration so much that we did it again with Evergreen Music, Bush to Bowl and Honey Australia in 2022 with a brand new design.

pittwater-eco-adventures.description: I had the pleasure of working with Pittwater Eco Adventures again for their new campaign ‘Preserve Wild Places’ with the primary goal to learn, understand and connect with Country as a first step to restoration and regeneration of the natural environment around us.The artwork itself is inspired by a secret waterfall tucked away in Kuringai National Park that overlooks a pristine bay and is home to Wallabies, Echidnas, Red Belly Black Snakes, Death Adders and threatened species like the Glossy Black Cockatoos.

wires-x-brentos-collaboration.description: In early December 2019, I collaborated with WIRES to launch a fundraiser called the Koala Care Package that consisted of Brentos branded merchandise along with official WIRES educational material (brochures, card and magnets).
Each care package contained one t-shirt, a fine art print, tote bag, postcard, stickers and printed WIRES material to raise awareness for wildlife rescue and conservation in NSW and Australia.

The packages were sold on a custom website I designed with 100% of profits going back to the WIRES Emergency Fund. We sold out our first run of care packages in just under 2 days and ended up selling over 100 packages and raising over $4,000.
Here are some illustrations that were used in the fundraiser:

surfing-australia.description: Surfing Australia’s nationwide community were badly affected by the bushfires of 2019 - 2020. In response they launched their Community Relief Fund aimed to raise funding to support their community. I jumped on board and helped them with some fun branding and an illustration for their campaign.

Buckettys-Brewing-x-The-Tawny-Frogmouth.description: I had the absolute pleasure of creating the cover artwork for Issue #7 of The Tawny Frogmouth magazine – a local Northern Beaches publication with a 50,000 strong circulation. The team really liked the artwork and so we decided to go all in and work with local brewery Buckettys to brew a Pale Ale with 100% of the profits going to WIRES. The rye Pale was a hit and the rallying from the community was incredible with all tins sold in less than a week.
